  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Reverse Linked List\n\nGiven the head of a singly linked list, return the head of the same values in reverse order.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: head = [2,4,6,8]\nOutput: [8,6,4,2]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: head = [7]\nOutput: [7]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: head = []\nOutput: []\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- The judge provides a `ListNode` class with `val` and `next` fields.\n- Node values fit in normal signed integer range.\n- The total number of nodes across one test case is kept small enough for local execution.\n\n## Follow-up\n\nCan you reverse the list without allocating another list of nodes?",
  "editorial": "Walk through the list while carrying the previous node. Redirect each `next` pointer toward the previous node and advance until the old tail becomes the new head.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def reverseList(self, head):\n        previous = None\n        current = head\n        while current:\n            nxt = current.next\n            current.next = previous\n            previous = current\n            current = nxt\n        return previous\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Keep track of the node that should follow the current node after reversal.",
    "The old head should eventually point to `None`."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def reverseList(self, head):\n        pass\n"
  },
  "entrypoint": {
    "class_name": "Solution",
    "method_name": "reverseList"
  },
  "checker": {
    "type": "exact"
  },
  "time_limit_ms": 2000,
  "memory_limit_mb": 256,
